@node Requirements "BeSel - Requirements"
@next Installation
@prev Features

  @{b}Requirements@{ub}
  ------------

  BeSel should run on all Amigas. The requirements are:

  - AmigaOS 1.2 or better

  - Some kind of Execute and Run commands available to execute
    scripts and run programs
    (OS 2.0 and better have Run resident in ROM)

  - Some scripts and programs you wish to use

@endnode

@node Installation "BeSel - Installation"
@next Usage
@prev Requirements

  @{b}Installation@{ub}
  ------------

  Installation is simple.

  You can copy BeSel executable and configuration files anywhere
  you want to. Just make sure you can run the program from there.

  To actually use BeSel, you need some scripts or programs you want
  to execute during startup. Then you can modify the configuration
  file (plain text) to your own needs.


  @{b}Structure of the configuration file@{ub}
  -----------------------------------

  OK, this might not be so simple but there is no GUI based
  editor either.

@{b}------clip-------------------------------------------------@{ub}
; Example configuration file for BeSel 0.17
; © MpL & Software With A :-)

F1              ; This is an entry for function key F1.
S:MoreAssigns   ; This is the script that should be
                ; executed if F1 is pressed.

; <- That means this is a comment.

EX              ; This is an entry to redefine the normal Execute
HD0:C/Execute13 ; command. Let's use this command instead of "Execute"
                ; for the following entries until we change it again.

F2
S:OldKick       ; This would now be "HD0:C/Execute13 S:OldKick" instead
                ; of "Execute S:OldKick".

EX              ; Lets remove Execute completely!
-               ; The following entries are not treated as scripts
                ; but executable files. You could use scripts as well
                ; if they had their s and e flags set.

F3
CoolProggy      ; This would be just "CoolProggy" without any "Execute".

EX
info
F4
df0:            ; This would be "info df0:". Isn't that easy?

EX              ; Redefine Execute once again.
+               ; Shortcut to restore the original Execute.
                ; You could of course write "Execute" instead of "+"
                ; to achieve the same thing.

F5              ; Another key.
; hmmmmm...
S:StartUp2      ; The script name should follow the key code
                ; on its own line (blanks and comments between
                ; allowed).

; These are for mouse.

ML              ; Entry for left mouse button.
S:Lefty         ; And the script for it.

DF              ; This means default.
S:TheUsualStuff ; If nothing else was done.
@{b}------clip-------------------------------------------------@{ub}

  You can have comments in the file by using ';' characters.
  You can also have blank lines.

  @{b}F1@{ub}, @{b}F2@{ub}, @{b}F3@{ub}, ..., @{b}F0@{ub} are codes for function keys F1-F10.
  Note that F10 is F0!

  @{b}ML@{ub}, @{b}MM@{ub}, @{b}MR@{ub} are codes for left, middle and right mouse
  buttons respectively. Then we have @{b}MB@{ub} which means both
  buttons, that is, left and right buttons simultaneously.

  Normally all entries are assumed to be scripts. For example,
  MyScript is executed by doing "Execute MyScript". With @{b}EX@{ub}
  you can redefine "Execute" to be something else or even remove
  it. This way you can use different versions of Execute commands
  or run executable programs.

  @{b}DF@{ub} is a code for default script. This one will be executed
  if no keys or buttons are being pressed.

  You probably should use full paths for the scripts and
  programs so that they can be found.

@endnode

@node Usage "BeSel - How to use it"
@next History
@prev Installation

  @{b}Usage@{ub}
  -----

  BeSel should be run from Shell only:

  @{fg highlight}BeSel [configuration_file] [QUIET]@{fg text}

  The @{" configuration file " link "Installation"} tells BeSel what scripts or
  programs to execute when certain keys or buttons are being
  pressed. If you have multiple keys or buttons pressed, the
  order in which they will be processed is F1, F2, ..., F10,
  left, right, middle and both mouse buttons. In theory you can
  execute 12 scripts or programs in one go if all keys and
  buttons are being pressed. You can have a default entry which
  will be used if no keys or buttons are pressed.

  If you do not give a configuration file as a parameter,
  BeSel will not execute anything but only sets the Shell RC
  environment variable to a value which can then be examined
  by the user. These are the values:

       Button pressed    Result
       --------------    ------

        F1            -> RC = 1
        F2            -> RC = 2
        .             .
        .             .
        F10           -> RC = 10
        Left button   -> RC = 11
        Middle button -> RC = 12
        Right button  -> RC = 13
        Left&Right    -> RC = 14

  To check for a certain value you could use something like this:

  IF $RC EQ <value>
      Do something...
  ELSE
      Something else...
  ENDIF

  Note that if you are still using OS version below 2.0 you
  probably can't use RC.

  Normally if you are pressing a key or button BeSel checks
  if that key or button has an entry in the configuration
  file. If such an entry can not be found BeSel reports
  an error. If you wish to ignore missing entries you can
  use the QUIET option. However, this will not suppress
  more serious error messages.

  If everything goes well, BeSel will not output any text and
  you should have your normal black screen during startup
  (at least with OS 2.0+). However, you can examine what really
  happened by checking BeSels return code (if you are using
  a configuration file, otherwise RC will be the key number).
  0 means that nothing _really_ happened, 5 (WARN) means that
  at least one script or program was executed. If BeSel can not
  allocate needed resources, fails to load the configuration
  file or Execute reports an error, BeSel will output an error
  message and set the return code to 20 (FAIL).

  An example of BeSel in Startup-Sequence:

@{b}----clip-------------------------------------------------@{ub}
$VER: CutDown Startup 40.0

C:SetPatch QUIET
C:Version >NIL:

FailAt 21

Assign >NIL: ENV: RAM:ENV

@{b}BeSel S:GameAssigns.cfg QUIET@{ub} ; Make some assigns if user
                              ; wants to play games.
C:IPrefs
C:LoadWB
EndCLI >NIL:
@{b}----clip-------------------------------------------------@{ub}

@endnode

@node History "BeSel - History"
@next Bugs
